3th century as <i>Cophill</i>, from Old English <i>copp</i> ‘peak’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Alternatively, a variant of   Cupples  , of Norman origin.","Americanized form of German, Dutch or Jewish   Koppel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cupples","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman orign): from Old French <i>curt peil</i> ‘short hair’, with post-medieval excrescent or genitival <i>-s</i>. See also   Copple   1.","Scottish: possibly a nickname from <i>cupples</i>, one of the pairs of sloping rafters, forming two sides of a triangle, which support the roof of a building.","Irish: possibly a variant of <b>Caplice</b>, apparently from an unidentified English surname. It is found mainly in Tipperary and northern Cork."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":26,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionL